      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>9</mn>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mn>3</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\sqrt {9}}=3,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/f99178110451bea99849a5cd0ee41666e4cecc5b" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:8.006ex; height:2.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle {\sqrt {9}}=3,}"></span> so 9 is a square number.
</p><p>A positive integer that has no square <a href="/wiki/Divisor" title="Divisor">divisors</a> except 1 is called <a href="/wiki/Square-free_integer" title="Square-free integer">square-free</a>.
</p><p>For a non-negative integer <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">n</span>, the <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">n</span>th square number is <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i><sup>2</sup></span>, with <span class="texhtml">0<sup>2</sup> = 0</span> being the <a href="/wiki/0_(number)" class="mw-redirect" title="0 (number)">zeroth</a> one. The concept of square can be extended to some other number systems. If <a href="/wiki/Rational_number" title="Rational number">rational</a> numbers are included, then a square is the ratio of two square integers, and, conversely, the ratio of two square integers is a square, for example, 
