<p>The difference between any perfect square and its predecessor is given by the identity <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i><sup>2</sup> − (<i>n</i> − 1)<sup>2</sup> = 2<i>n</i> − 1</span>. Equivalently, it is possible to count square numbers by adding together the last square, the last square's root, and the current root, that is, <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i><sup>2</sup> = (<i>n</i> − 1)<sup>2</sup> + (<i>n</i> − 1) + <i>n</i></span>.
</p>
