<p>There are several <a href="/wiki/Recursion#Recursion_in_mathematics" title="Recursion">recursive</a> methods for computing square numbers. For example, the <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">n</span>th square number can be computed from the previous square by <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i><sup>2</sup> = (<i>n</i> − 1)<sup>2</sup> + (<i>n</i> − 1) + n = (<i>n</i> − 1)<sup>2</sup> + (2<i>n</i> − 1)</span>. Alternatively, the <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">n</span>th square number can be calculated from the previous two by doubling the <span class="texhtml">(<i>n</i> − 1)</span>th square, subtracting the <span class="texhtml">(<i>n</i> − 2)</span>th square number, and adding 2, because <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i><sup>2</sup> = 2(<i>n</i> − 1)<sup>2</sup> − (<i>n</i> − 2)<sup>2</sup> + 2</span>. For example,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="texhtml">2 × 5<sup>2</sup> − 4<sup>2</sup> + 2 = 2 × 25 − 16 + 2 = 50 − 16 + 2 = 36 = 6<sup>2</sup></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>The square minus one of a number <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">m</span> is always the product of <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle m-1}">
